snippet.textDisplay: When the lover meets the Beloved, his own light is extinguished he becomes nothing, he is "Fana fil'llah."   His own desires are extinguished, chaap and tilak symbolising the dunya (world) have now evaporated.  The Beloved could here be Allah Taa'la or even his Shaykh (Hz Pir Nizamuddin Awliya RA).   The "tawajjuh" of the Shaykh is enough to propel you to the true Beloved, so even this attentive gaze is enough to merit the pen of Amir Khusrao RA

snippet.textDisplay: I don’t know where to begin to make a humble comment on a masterpiece of a song.  I grew up in India, living in the U.S. and forever I listened to rock and hard rock music. And then came this amazing gift to me. Came at a very dark time in my life and opened my eyes to what matters - giving everything away and embracing the master with nothing but devotion. The poem is a gem and the song rendering by these great artists elevates this gem to a level where it touches and changes your soul. I need not do anything but soak in the music into my innermost being.
